image.altText: A birds eye view of a navy ship.

props.synopsis: Australia's troubled Hunter-class frigate program has avoided being axed following a sweeping review of the navy's combat surface fleet, with at least six and possibly several more of the large and expensive warships to be built over coming decades.

title.children: Controversial British Hunter-class warship program survives as government prepares to unveil Australia's 'Future Navy'

image.altText: worker smooths concrete at a slab pour with other workers in background.

props.synopsis: Workers shoulder the burden of paying for the things we want: schools, hospitals and a civil, safe society. But as our population ages and more people need support, can income tax continue to fund our needs?

title.children: Australia's ageing population set to challenge reliance on workers' wages

image.altText: A side profile of Mr Chandler-Mather, who is looking off camera.

props.synopsis: The Greens say they won't support the government's 'help-to-buy' housing scheme, which they say will push up house prices, unless the government is willing to make changes to negative gearing and capital gains tax concessions.

title.children: Greens demand limits to negative gearing in exchange for support for 'help-to-buy' housing bill

image.altText: A young boy looking at a sheet of paper with words on it

props.synopsis: One third of Australian students are failing to learn to read proficiently, at an estimated cost to the economy of $40 billion, according to a new study.

title.children: 'Preventable tragedy': One third of Australian students are failing to learn to read proficiently, report says

image.altText: A single firefighter fights a huge fire as it destroys wooden and plastic shelters

props.synopsis: In the Rohingya refugee camps of Cox's Bazar, more than 1 million people are living in worsening conditions. However, the world wasn't watching when tragedy unfolded.

title.children: A massive fire left 7,000 people, including thousands of children, homeless. Australia didn't seem to notice

image.altText: Two toddlers eating apples segments

props.synopsis: Research suggests young children are going hungry in early childhood centres, and being given food that doesn't meet dietary standards.

title.children: Young kids failing to get adequate nutrition in early childcare centres, research suggests

image.altText: A man with a large brimmed hat and blue working shirt sits on a hay bail holding a white border collie

props.synopsis: A pure white border collie stands out among grazier Frank Finger's pack of kelpies. And Lucky — a deaf puppy from season two of Muster Dogs — has settled into his new home and is even mustering cattle.

title.children: 'I called him Lucky because I was lucky to have him': This deaf collie now musters cattle

image.altText: Glenn Maxwell with his arms raised holding a helmet and cricket bat.

props.synopsis: Glenn Maxwell has blasted a record-breaking T20 ton to inspire Australia to a series win against the West Indies.

title.children: Maxwell blasts record T20I ton against West Indies

image.altText: Tara Gallagher, left, organiser of the Croissant Run Club smiling and talking to a fellow runner outside a Sydney cafe

props.synopsis: Loneliness is now a public health priority for the UN, and with one-third of Australians feeling lonely some or all of the time, there are growing calls for the federal government to do the same.

title.children: 'Not about the run': Australians are tackling 'huge' issue of loneliness amid calls for government to do more

image.altText: A man standing inside bushland with a hat and a grey button-up shirt stares at the camera.

props.synopsis: Brunswick Heads locals clash with a developer planning to turn an 18-hectatre stretch of bushland with threatened species into housing to alleviate the region's homeless rate.

title.children: 'We're sick of destroying it': Community fears impact of new housing development on 'unique ecosystem'

image.altText: Grainy footage shows a man in a suit lying on the ground, one hand to his ear holding a phone.

props.synopsis: Anthony Albanese says the opposition frontbencher owes the public an explanation for why he was laid out on a footpath in Canberra's entertainment district late after a parliament sitting day, with Peter Dutton revealing he'll speak to the 56-year-old about the incident.

title.children: PM says Joyce must explain himself after former deputy leader filmed lying on footpath

image.altText: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton speaks to the media at a press conference

props.synopsis: The Coalition will unwind laws allowing workers to ignore unreasonable out-of-hours contact from their bosses, the Opposition Leader says, committing his party to undoing the 'right to disconnect' if it wins the next federal election.

title.children: Peter Dutton says Coalition will repeal 'right to disconnect' laws if it wins government

image.altText: Harold Mitchell walks out of glass doors of the court building into light rain while wearing a suit.

props.synopsis: Advertising veteran and philanthropist Harold Mitchell, described as "a renaissance man", dies after undergoing knee replacement surgery.

title.children: Advertising icon and philanthropist Harold Mitchell dies aged 81

image.altText: An indigenous elder speaking at a Voice event.

props.synopsis: Ngunnawal elder Aunty Violet Sheridan says she's considering running as an independent in the upcoming ACT election, but the announcement has seen tensions between First Nations people bubble over.

title.children: Ngunnawal elder Aunty Violet clashes with Ngambri man as she announces possible ACT election candidacy

image.altText: Taylor Swift dressed in a blue dress looks over her shoulder while standing in front of a sign saying Taylor Swift Eras Tour

props.synopsis: Taylor Swift is at the centre of a far-right conspiracy theory that claims the singer is part of an elaborate plot to rig football games and deliver Joe Biden the presidency. Here's how it unfolded.

title.children: Why far-right figures will be particularly concerned by Taylor Swift at the Super Bowl ahead of 2024 election

image.altText: Donald Trump points his index fingers up as he speaks into a microphone with an animated expression

props.synopsis: Donald Trump says that, as president, he warned NATO allies that he "would encourage" Russia "to do whatever the hell they want" to countries that are "delinquent" as he ramped up his attacks on foreign aid and longstanding international alliances.

title.children: Donald Trump says he warned NATO ally: Spend more on defence or Russia can 'do whatever the hell they want'

image.altText: a group of girls allegedly assault a woman at burwood train station on saturday february 10

props.synopsis: NSW Police say officers were called to the station at about 9pm on Saturday to reports of a brawl, and arrested four girls at the scene.

title.children: Four girls, including 11yo, charged after alleged assault at Sydney train station

image.altText: Clive Palmer poses for a photograph in front of a statue of Jeff the dinosaur.

props.synopsis: Billionaire Clive Palmer's Queensland resort suddenly fired 125 employees in August, with the workplace tribunal criticising the handling of several terminations.

title.children: 'Unfairly' sacked employees from Clive Palmer's resort awarded thousands of dollars compensation

image.altText: A composite of a  tree-lined dirt track extending away into the bush, and a thin smiling woman with blonde hair.

props.synopsis: A vigil has been held for Samantha Murphy in her home town of Ballarat as the investigation into the disappearance of the 51-year-old woman enters its second week.

title.children: Vigil held for missing woman Samantha Murphy as PM extends sympathies

image.altText: A Manly rugby league players stands holding an award.

props.synopsis: Experts say Manly Sea Eagles player Keith Titmuss died from an illness that is "massively underestimated".

title.children: 'Under-reported': The deadly illness affecting young, healthy Australians

image.altText: A snapping turtle with a spiky shell is laid out on a towel, opening its mouth wide open.

props.synopsis: The dinosaur-looking creature, native to the US south, was spotted bathing in a lake in Cumbria by a local dog walker.

title.children: Woman fishes alligator snapping turtle out of English lake using a shopping basket

image.altText: King Charles walks alongside a clergyman in formal wear

props.synopsis: King Charles expresses his heartfelt thanks for the messages of support in his first personal statement on his cancer diagnosis.

title.children: King shares thanks for messages of support after cancer diagnosis, makes first public outing

image.altText: A road sign that reads "river closed sat and sun"

props.synopsis: Emergency services were called to the Murray River in Moama after reports a man had been seriously injured in the Southern 80 waterski race.

title.children: Man dies in waterskiing event on Victorian–NSW border

image.altText: A composite image of a live export vessel and sheep behind bars

props.synopsis: After more than a month at sea, thousands of cattle and sheep on board the MV Bahijah are set to be allowed on land in WA this week. Here's how the journey unfolded.

title.children: After five weeks stuck at sea, thousands of livestock are set to land in WA

image.altText: Cody Walker playing for the Indigenous All Stars.

props.synopsis: Indigenous All Stars playmaker Cody Walker is out of Friday's clash with the Māori side in Townsville after the South Sydney star picked up a calf injury.

title.children: Cody Walker among five players pulling out of NRL's All Stars game

image.altText: A middle-aged man stands on the beach holding a bucket and rubbish tongs.

props.synopsis: Andy Orr did not dive into a life of luxury when he received an inheritance but instead dedicated his time to cleaning up the beaches of Sydney Harbour.

title.children: Inheritance allows 'Guardian of Sydney Harbour' to quit his job and pick up plastic

image.altText: Molly Picklum gives shakas to the camera while on a surfboard in the ocean. She is wearing a Red Bull helmet.

props.synopsis: Molly Picklum loses the final of the Pipe Pro in Hawaii, but cements her place in history with the first perfect ride by a woman at the famous surf break.

title.children: 'Absolutely insane': Aussie surfer Molly Picklum makes history with first women's perfect 10 at Pipeline event

image.altText: a surfer on a massive wave with his partner in the foreground sitting in a little tender boat

props.synopsis: Torren Martyn and his partner Aiyana Powell barely knew how to sail before embarking on 12-month voyage through the tropics. On their little boat Calypte, the couple braved wild weather, survived a brush with death and scored some of the best waves of their lives.

title.children: With no sailing experience, an Aussie surfer set off on a 9,000km adventure and had the trip of a lifetime
